title: Hong Kong stays vigilant against avian influenza threat (with photo)
content_text:
p>
The Secretary for Health, Welfare and Food, Dr York Chow, today (February 1) 
convened a meeting in view of the latest avian influenza outbreaks in the 
region. At the meeting, representatives from relevant departments including the 
Department of Health (DH) and Agriculture, Fisheries and Conservation Department 
(AFCD) provided their latest report on Hong Kong's preparedness against the 
infectious disease as well as risk assessment of a possible outbreak in Hong 
Kong. The chairman of the Scientific Committee on Emerging and Zoonotic Diseases

Kong. The chairman of the Scientific Committee on Emerging and Zoonotic Diseases 
formed under the Centre for Health Protection of DH, Professor Yuen Kwok-yung, 
attended the meeting and gave his expert assessment and view on the latest 
threat of the deadly virus. Dr Chow noted that recent reports of avian flu cases in other places of the 
Mainland and overseas as well as the detection of H5N1 virus in local wild birds 
had indicated that the disease remained a threat to our community. Experts exchanged their views on the present surveillance programme on wild

birds and agreed that the programme had been working well. The AFCD had tested about 13,500 dead birds in the past three years and found 
the presence of H5N1 in 33 of them.  The CHP reported that the World Health Organisation (WHO) has not made any 
change in antiviral treatment recommendations for H5N1 patients as there was no 
indication that oseltamivir resistance was widespread as suspected in the two 
recent Egypt cases or elsewhere. The meeting was informed that the antiviral guidelines promulgated by the CHP

would remain valid. The current antiviral stockpile level is over 15 million 
doses -- including Tamiflu and Relenza. The target stockpile of approximately 20 
million doses is expected to be achieved by the middle of this year. Dr Chow noted that the risk of poultry outbreaks and human infections of H5N1 in 
Hong Kong has not been changed, adding that the risk would most likely continue 
to exist in the region, with more cases detected during winter period. "We should stay vigilant against avian influenza and update our preparedness

plan regularly to fine-tune on areas that we consider appropriate," he said. Hong Kong has maintained a zero case record on H5N1 avian influenza human 
infection as well as poultry infection in our local farms since early 2003 
although the virus was continued to be found on a small number of dead migratory 
and wild birds. Since 2003, the WHO has confirmed a total of 270 human cases of H5N1 infection

from 10 countries, with 164 (60.7 per cent) of them being fatal cases. Dr Chow called for concerted effort from the community to guard against avian 
flu in Hong Kong. "Members of the public should strictly observe personal and environmental 
hygiene, and stay away from dead birds, avoid contact with wild birds and live 
poultry and their droppings. "They are also urged not to feed or release wild birds, and surrender their pet 
birds to AFCD's animal management centres for disposal if they no longer want to

birds to AFCD's animal management centres for disposal if they no longer want to keep pet birds. Besides, they should refrain from keeping backyard poultry," he said. Ends/Thursday, February 1, 2007
